<div class="info-section" slot="info">
<h2>CSS Border Radius Generator - Create Custom Rounded Shapes Online</h2>
    <p>The CSS Border Radius Generator lets you visually design and customize border-radius values for HTML elements with a live preview that updates in real time. Create perfect circles, smooth pill shapes, rounded rectangles, organic blobs, and complex asymmetric shapes — then copy the generated CSS code directly into your project with a single click.</p>

    <h3>What Is CSS Border Radius?</h3>
    <p>The CSS border-radius property rounds the corners of an element's border box. It is one of the most commonly used CSS properties in modern web design, enabling designers to move away from the sharp, boxy look of early web interfaces toward the softer, more approachable aesthetic that dominates contemporary UI design. The property can be applied to any block-level or inline-block element, including divs, buttons, images, inputs, and cards.</p>
    <p>The border-radius property accepts a wide range of values. You can use pixel values for fixed-size rounding (e.g., border-radius: 8px), percentage values for proportional rounding that scales with the element's size (e.g., border-radius: 50% creates a circle from a square element), and em or rem values for rounding that scales with the font size. You can also use the slash syntax to create elliptical corners, where the horizontal and vertical radii of each corner are different.</p>
    <p>When you set individual values for each corner, the shorthand order is top-left, top-right, bottom-right, bottom-left — going clockwise from the top-left corner. This allows you to create asymmetric shapes where each corner has a different radius, enabling a wide range of creative design possibilities beyond simple rounded rectangles.</p>

    <h3>Border Radius Controls</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>All-corners slider for quickly setting a uniform radius on all four corners simultaneously.</li>
        <li>Individual corner sliders for top-left, top-right, bottom-right, and bottom-left for precise asymmetric control.</li>
        <li>Live preview that updates in real time as you adjust the sliders, showing exactly how the shape will look.</li>
        <li>Quick preset buttons for common shapes: Circle (50%), Rounded (20px), Blob (asymmetric), and Reset (0px).</li>
        <li>Automatic CSS code generation that outputs the most concise valid CSS for your current settings.</li>
        <li>One-click copy button to copy the generated CSS code to your clipboard instantly.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>How to Use the Border Radius Generator</h3>
    <p>Creating custom border-radius shapes with this tool is intuitive and requires no CSS knowledge to get started.</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Step 1: Use the "All Corners" slider to set a uniform radius for all four corners at once. This is the fastest way to create a simple rounded rectangle or circle.</li>
        <li>Step 2: For more complex shapes, use the individual corner sliders to set different radii for each corner. The preview updates in real time so you can see the shape as you adjust.</li>
        <li>Step 3: Try the quick preset buttons to jump to common shapes — Circle for a perfect round shape, Rounded for a standard card style, Blob for an organic asymmetric shape, or Reset to start over.</li>
        <li>Step 4: Review the generated CSS code in the output panel below the preview. The code is automatically simplified — if all corners are equal, it outputs a single value; otherwise it outputs all four values.</li>
        <li>Step 5: Click "Copy CSS" to copy the generated code to your clipboard, then paste it into your stylesheet or CSS-in-JS code.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Designing Rounded Corners</h3>
    <p>Border radius is one of the most versatile CSS properties, used in virtually every modern web interface.</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Card components — apply a consistent border-radius (typically 8px to 16px) to card elements to give them a modern, approachable appearance that lifts them off the background.</li>
        <li>Buttons — rounded buttons (border-radius: 6px to 8px) feel more clickable and friendly than sharp-cornered buttons, and pill-shaped buttons (border-radius: 999px) are a popular modern style.</li>
        <li>Avatar images — apply border-radius: 50% to square profile images to create circular avatars, which are standard in social media and messaging interfaces.</li>
        <li>Input fields — slightly rounded input fields (border-radius: 4px to 8px) feel more polished and modern than sharp-cornered inputs.</li>
        <li>Badges and tags — pill-shaped badges with high border-radius values are commonly used for labels, status indicators, and category tags.</li>
        <li>Decorative shapes — use asymmetric border-radius values to create organic blob shapes for backgrounds, illustrations, and decorative UI elements.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Crafting Smooth Border Radii</h3>
    <p>Consistency is key when using border-radius in a design system. Choose a small set of radius values — for example, 4px for small elements, 8px for medium elements, 16px for large cards, and 50% for circular elements — and apply them consistently throughout your interface. This creates a cohesive visual language that makes your UI feel intentional and well-designed rather than arbitrary.</p>
    <p>When creating circular elements, remember that border-radius: 50% only creates a perfect circle when the element is square (equal width and height). If the element is rectangular, 50% will create an ellipse. To create a circle from a non-square element, you need to explicitly set equal width and height, or use a fixed pixel value that is at least half the smaller dimension.</p>
    <p>For the blob and organic shape presets, the asymmetric values create shapes that feel natural and hand-drawn. These are popular in modern web design for hero sections, background decorations, and illustration-style UI elements. You can further customize the blob shape by adjusting individual corner values until you find a shape that fits your design aesthetic.</p>

    

    <h3>CSS Generated Instantly — No Server</h3>
    <p>CSS is generated locally. No data leaves your browser.</p>

            <h3>Frequently Asked Questions</h3>
            <div class="faq-list">
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What does border-radius do in CSS?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>border-radius rounds the corners of an element's border box. A value of 50% on a square element creates a perfect circle. You can set all four corners at once or control each corner independently for asymmetric shapes.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is the difference between shorthand and longhand border-radius?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>Shorthand (border-radius: 10px) sets all four corners equally. Longhand properties (border-top-left-radius, border-top-right-radius, etc.) set each corner individually. The shorthand also supports an elliptical syntax (border-radius: 10px / 20px) for oval corners.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What units can I use for border-radius?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>You can use px (fixed pixels), % (relative to element size), em (relative to font size), or rem (relative to root font size). Percentage values are relative to the element's dimensions, so 50% always creates a circle/ellipse regardless of element size.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can I create pill-shaped buttons with border-radius?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>Yes. Set border-radius to a large value like 9999px or 50px on a button. As long as the value is larger than half the button's height, the ends will be fully rounded, creating the classic pill shape.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Why does my border-radius look different on different elements?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>Border-radius appearance depends on the element's dimensions. The same pixel value looks more rounded on a small element than a large one. Use percentage values if you want consistent rounding relative to the element's size.</p></div>
                </div>
            </div>

